WTH! That's garbage. Maybe I missed something? Well you can't always rely on ready-made scripts... Let's crack it from scratch. n is not that large, so I used this [site](http://factordb.com/) to factor n and this tells that n is a perfect square. But wait! n = p * q where p and q should be distinct primes for RSA, but we have p=q. That's why the tool failed. To crack RSA when p=q, `phi = p * (q - 1)` instead of `phi = (p - 1) * (q - 1)`. Now as n is not that large, and e is very small, we can use wiener attack to crack it.

Running my [script](./data/rsa_solve.py) (takes some time...)
```
$ sage rsa_solve.py
hsctf{square_number_time}
```
